com.datasweep.compatibility.pnuts

Interface Functions


  • public interface Functions
    This interface is used to provide api documentation for the functions provided in the pnuts scripting environment.

      • adjustLotDialog

        Response adjustLotDialog(Lot lot)
        NOT CURRENTLY IMPLEMENTED

        Displays a dialog allowing attributes of the specified Lot to be updated. Changes may be made to the Lot attributes Lot Name, Comment, Notes and Promised Time. Other Lot attributes are displayed, but cannot be changed. Note: The dialog generated is fixed format and cannot be changed. Lot attributes not included that require update must be accessed via a user generated dialog or form. 

         
      //get the Lot object for the LotName specified
      //display adjust dialog for this Lot
      //check the response and display any errors
      lotToAdjust = "LotName"
      lotObj =  getLotByName(lotToAdjust)
      response = adjustLotDialog(lotObj)
      checkAndDisplayResponse(response)
        Parameters:
        lot - the Lot to be modified
        Returns:
        a Response object containing any errors returned
        See Also:
        createLotDialog(Order), createLotDialog(Order, String, String, int, int, String)

      • buildChartFromGrid

        void buildChartFromGrid(DsChart chart,
                        DsGrid grid,
                        int labelColumn,
                        int startRow,
                        int startColumn,
                        int endRow,
                        int endColumn,
                        boolean bSwap)
        Plots data from a DsGrid on a DsChart. 
         
      // get the grid, clear and format it
      DsGrid =  getGrid("grid")
      DsGrid.clearGrid()
      DsGrid.setNumberOfRows(10)
      DsGrid.setNumberOfColumns(4)
 
      //create mock labels and data
      for (x=0;x<10;x++)
      {
          dataLabel = "June " + x.toString() + ", 2000"
          value1 = (x * 2) + 1
          value2 = (x * 3) + 2
          value3 = (x * 4) + 3
 
          //write the data to the grid
          DsGrid.setCellText(x, 0, dataLabel)
          DsGrid.setCellText(x, 1, value1)
          DsGrid.setCellText(x, 2, value2)
          DsGrid.setCellText(x, 3, value3)
      }
 
      //get the chart and plot the data
      DsChart =  getChart("chart")
      DsChart.setChartStyle(2)
      numRows = DsGrid.getNumberOfRows()
      numCols = DsGrid.getNumberOfColumns()
      buildChartFromGrid(DsChart, DsGrid, 0, 1, 1, numRows - 1, numCols - 1, false)
        Parameters:
        chart - is the chart to format
        grid - is the grid to use as the source for the data
        labelColumn - is the column that contains the axis labels, use -1 if no axis labels are provided
        startRow - is the starting row of the data
        startColumn - is the starting column of the data
        endRow - is the ending row of the data
        endColumn - is the ending column of the data
        bSwap - specifies whether to swap the axis

                   java.lang.String password)

      • checkAndDisplayResponse

        void checkAndDisplayResponse(Response r)
        Checks a Response object for errors, and if errors exist, displays them in a dialog. If the Response object contains no errors script execution will continue and no dialog will be displayed. If the Response object does contain errors a dialog with all of the error messages will be displayed. Script execution will not continue until the user closes the dialog. 
         
      response =  Unit.save()
      checkAndDisplayResponse(response)
        Parameters:
        r - is the response object to test for errors.

      • closeDialog

        void closeDialog(int value)
        This function will close a dialog form. It should normally be called from a script attached to the click event of a button on the form (typically the OK and/or Cancel button). You should not use this function to close a form.
        Parameters:
        value - This int value is passed back to the script that invoked the dialog using the showAsDialog function. It may be used to determine how the dialog was closed (e.g., OK or Cancel).

      • closeForm

        void closeForm()
        This function will close the current form. If the current form is stacked on another form the it will be activated. The showAsForm function may be used to open/stack forms. Do not use this function to close a form that is displayed as a dialog.

        This function displays a dialog that allows the user to specify attributes for a new Lot.         the created lot object is returned if the creation was successful, otherwise a null is returned. If an error occured a response object may be retrieved using the getLastResponse() function.

      • createTemporaryFile

        java.io.File createTemporaryFile(java.lang.String fileExtension)
        Creates a temporary file with the extension specified. The function takes a file extension as its single argument. The function finds the OS's temporary directory and creates a temporary file of the form (tempXXX.ext where ext is the user supplied extension - note the exact file name is created by the method java.io.File.createTempFile). The file is created using the deleteOnExit flag provided by java (which will cause the file to be deleted when the VM exits). If the file extension is null or empty then then '.tmp' will be used.

      • getUserTransaction

        Response getUserTransaction(boolean allowNesting)
        The function gets a UserTransaction object. The object that is returned in the Response object.
        Parameters:
        allowNesting - If this flag is set to true, the system would increment the count each time the UserTransation.begin is invoked. The first invocation will begin the transaction. Any subsequence call just incremented the count.

        If this flag is set to true, the system would decrement the count each time the UserTransation.commit is invoked. The last invocation will commit the transaction.

        Returns:
        a Response object containing UserTransaction or any errors returned.

      • cursorAutoMode

        void cursorAutoMode(boolean flag)
        Sets wait cursor behavior. The default is for cursorAutoMode to be true. When true the system automatically creates a wait cursor when a script event is started and returns the cursor to default mode when the script completes. If you would like to manually control the cursor then set auto mode to false and use the functions cursorDefault and cursorWait. Use the function getCursorAutoMode to return the current automode setting.

      • cursorDefault

        void cursorDefault()
        Sets the mouse cursor to the default arrow.

      • cursorWait

        void cursorWait()
        Sets the mouse cursor to an hour glass.

        Returns:
        the DateTimePicker control is returned.

      • dcInstanceDialog

        Response dcInstanceDialog(RuntimeDCS rdcs,
                          DCInstance dci)
        NOT CURRENTLY IMPLEMENTED

        This displays a dialog that allows the user to create, edit, or delete a DCInstance. If a DCInstance is passed into the function then that DCInstance may be edited or deleted. If a null is passed in for the DCInstance then a new DCInstance is created. The dialog allows the user to edit/modify all DataCollectionItem except for BINARY data. If the user presses either the Ok or Delete button then a Response object is returned, however if the Cancel button is pressed then a null is returned.

        Parameters:
        rdcs - is a RuntimeDCS object. If a null is passed in for the RuntimeDCS then a null is immediately returned without showing the dialog.
        dci - is the DCInstance object to be edited or deleted or null if a new DCInstance should be created.
        Returns:
        a Response object containing the results of the RuntimeDCS save() function call if the user edited, created or deleted the DCInstance. The return will be null if the user pressed the Cancel button.

      • filterItems

        java.util.Vector filterItems(java.util.Vector items,
                             java.util.Vector categories,
                             java.lang.String methodName,
                             boolean bInclusive,
                             boolean bIncludeNull)
        This function returns the objects in the items array when running the methodName function results in a value that is included in the categories Vector.
        Parameters:
        items - a Vector of homogenous objects.
        categories - is a Vector or categories to include.
        methodName - is the name of a function that can be invoked on the objects in the items Vector (the function must return an object)
        bInclusive - if true then results in the categories will be included if false then results not in the categories will be included.
        bIncludeNull - is true then null results will be included.
        Returns:
        a Vector of result objects is returned.

      • filterItemsByTime

        java.util.Vector filterItemsByTime(java.util.Vector items,
                                   java.lang.String methodName,
                                   Time minTime,
                                   Time maxTime)
        Returns the objects in the items Vector whose time (obtained by invoking methodName) is in the range minTime to maxTime.
        Parameters:
        items - is a Vector of objects to filter
        methodName - is the name of a function in the objects in the items Vector that return a Time object.
        minTime - is the minimum time (inclusive) to use for filtering if minTime is null then a time of 1/1/100 is used.
        maxTime - is the maximum time (exclusive) to use for filtering if maxTime is null then a time of 1/1/9999 is used.

      • getArrayDataFromActive

        java.util.Vector getArrayDataFromActive(java.lang.String sqlStatement,
                                        boolean maintainNullValues)
        Runs the specified sqlstatement query on the default active database for this client.
        Parameters:
        sqlStatement - is a syntactically correct SQL statement
        maintainNullValues - is a flag to instruct the server to maintain the SQL null value. If the value is true, the server will maintain SQL null value for the return data array. If the value is false, it works just like the other getArrayDataFromActive method signatures.
        Returns:
        a Vector of String array

      • getCategories

        java.util.Vector getCategories(java.util.Vector items,
                               java.lang.String methodName,
                               java.lang.Object nullValue)
        This function returns a Vector containing all of the unique categories of the provided Vector of items. The function is invoked and its result is placed in the resultant vector (if that result is not already in the vector). If the nullValue parameter is not null then that value is used as the category if invoking methodName on any of the items results in a null.
        Parameters:
        items - a Vector of homogenous objects.
        methodName - is the name of a function that can be invoked on the objects in the items Vector (the function must return an object)
        nullValue - is the value to use as the category for null results if null results shouldn't be included then set this parameter to null.
        Returns:
        a Vector of result objects is returned.

      • getCursorAutoMode

        boolean getCursorAutoMode()
        Gets wait cursor behavior. The default is for cursorAutoMode to be true. When true the system automatically creates a wait cursor when a script event is started and returns the cursor to default mode when the script completes. If you would like to manually control the cursor then set auto mode to false and use the functions cursorDefault and cursorWait. Use the function cursorAutoMode to return the current automode setting.

      • getForm

        Form getForm(java.lang.String formName)
        This function retrieves the Form with the specified name. The returned form is a new instance of the specified DS form and is not the active form until you call either showAsForm or showAsDialog. To obtain the active form, use the function getActiveForm instead.
        Parameters:
        formName - is the name of the Form to retrieve.
        Returns:
        is a Form object or null if no DS form is found with the specified name.

      • getFormProperty

        java.lang.Object getFormProperty(java.lang.String key)
        This function retrieve a form property for the current form. If there is no current for or if the current form does not have a property matching the key name then null is returned. To set a property see setFormProperty.
        Parameters:
        key - is the name of the property
        Returns:
        the property specified by key

      • getFormProperty

        java.lang.Object getFormProperty(Form form,
                                 java.lang.String key)
        This function retrieve a form property for the specified form. If the form is is null or the form does not have a property matching the key name then null is returned. To set a property see setFormProperty.
        Parameters:
        form - is the form to search for the property
        key - is the name of the property
        Returns:
        the property specified by key

      • getIncompleteLots

        java.util.Vector getIncompleteLots(java.lang.String partNumber)
        This helper function searches the database for incomplete order items for the specified part number. Where incomplete is defined as quantityOrdered is greater than quantityInProgress. For each orderItem that satisfies the incomplete criteria each lot that has been created for that order item is returned. If no incomplete order items are found or if there are no lots for any incomplete order items an empty vector is returned
        Parameters:
        partNumber - is the partNumber to search for
        Returns:
        a Vector of Lot objects is returned

If no incomplete order items are found or if there are no lots for any incomplete order items an empty vector is returned
        Parameters:
        bomName - is the name of the bill of materials to search for
        bomRevision - is the revision of the bill of materials to search for

        a Vector of Lot objects is returned

                                 java.lang.String bomRevision)
        Deprecated. 
        This function returns a template BOM by bom name & revision. This release will only support a flat BillOfMaterials, so only the top level template BOM will be returned. If the template BOM does not exist, it will be created by the middleware. Subsequence call to this function will not cause the tempalte BOM be recreated.

      • groupItems

        java.util.Vector groupItems(java.util.Vector items,
                            java.util.Vector categories,
                            java.lang.String methodName,
                            java.lang.Object nullValue)
        This function returns a Vector of Vectors of items. The source items vector is broken into groups based on the categories provided. The function methodName is invoked on the item objects and the results are compared against the contents of the categories Vector (if categories is null then all of the results are used to determine the categories)
        Parameters:
        items - a Vector of homogenous objects.
        categories - is a Vector or categories to include.
        methodName - is the name of a function that can be invoked on the objects in the items Vector (the function must return an object)
        nullValue - is the value to use as the category for null results if null results shouldn't be included then set this parameter to null.

      • launchAssociatedProgram

        void launchAssociatedProgram(java.lang.String filePath)
        This function launches the program associated with the filepath. For example if the filepath is "c:\instructions.pdf" and Acrobat Reader is installed and associated with pdf files then if you call launchAssociatedProgram("c:\instructions.pdf"), Acrobat Reader will be launched and the file instructions.pdf will be loaded. The function is not supported for thin clients.
        Parameters:
        filePath - is the fully qualified path to the file to find an association for

      • launchInternetExplorer

        void launchInternetExplorer(java.lang.String url,
                            boolean addressBar,
                            boolean statusBar,
                            boolean toolBar)
        This function launches Internet Explorer and loads the specified URL (note that if the url is a file path then IE will try to load a plug-in to render the file). So if the URL is "www.rockwellautomation.com" then Internet Explorer will be launched and the rockwell automation homepage will be displayed. However, if the URL is "c:\instructions.pdf" and the Acrobat Reader plug-in for Internet Explorer is configured then Internet Explorer will be launched and the pdf document instrucions.pdf will be displayed
        Parameters:
        url - is the URL to navigate to
        addressBar - determines if the Internet Explorer Address Bar will be displayed
        statusBar - determines if the Internet Explorer status bar will be displayed
        toolBar - determines if the Internet Explorer tool bar will be displayed (note this flag only controls the display of the normal Internet Explorer tool bar, if Internet Explorer is configured with any third party tool bars they will still be displayed).

      • parseString

        java.util.Vector parseString(java.lang.String theString,
                             java.lang.String tokens)
        This function parses the source String into a Vector of String arrays. Each element of the Vector represents a line in the source String (a line is terminated by a carriage return, line feed or a carriage return immediately followed by a line feed. Each string array consists of the line which has been parsed (tokenized) based on the provided delimeter.
        Parameters:
        theString - is the source string to parse
        tokens - is a string containing the separator tokens
        Returns:
        a Vector containing the parsed lines in the source string

      • receiveBulkLot

        Response receiveBulkLot(java.math.BigDecimal quantity,
                        Part part,
                        boolean isBOMFullyPopulated,
                        Carrier carrier)
        This function create a new standalone bulk Lot. The status of the Lot will be "Received" and the inventory status will be "RIP". To obtained the created lot, call getResult() on the response object.
        Parameters:
        quantity - is the lot quantity.
        part - is a Part object.
        isBOMFullyPopulated - is a flag instructing the middleware to create a full runtime BOM for this Lot or not. If the value is false, an empty runtime BOM will be created. An empty runtime BOM means the runtime BOM without any item even though the BillOfMaterials has defined one or more items.
        carrier - is a Carrier object where the lot will be contained.
        Returns:
        A Response object that indicates the status of the transaction.

      • sendEmail

        Response sendEmail(java.lang.String toAddress,
                   java.lang.String subject,
                   java.lang.String message)
        This function sends an email message. Call the function setEmailFromAddress to include the sender email address in the header of the email message. Example: setEmailFromAddress("senderName@domain.com") sendEmail("name@place.com", "subject", "message")
        Parameters:
        toAddress - is the address of the email recipient it must be of the form "name@place.com" or an error will occur.
        subject - is the subject line of the email message.
        message - is the message to send.
        Returns:
        A Response object that indicates the status of the message send
        See Also:
        sendEmail(String, String, String, String, String, boolean, Vector)

      • sendEmail

        Response sendEmail(java.lang.String toAddress,
                   java.lang.String ccAddress,
                   java.lang.String bccAddress,
                   java.lang.String subject,
                   java.lang.String message,
                   boolean useHTML,
                   java.util.Vector attachments)
        This function sends an email message with attachments. Each attachment can be a file or a WorkInstruction object. Call the function setEmailFromAddress to include the sender email address in the header of the email message. Example: setEmailFromAddress("senderName@domain.com") attachments = vector() fileAttachment = openFileDialogEx() attachemnts.add(fileAttachment) workInstructionAttachment = getWorkInstruction(�workInstructionName?) attachments.add(workInstructionAttachment) response = sendEmail("name@place.com", "subject", "message", attachments) checkAndDisplayResponse(response)
        Parameters:
        toAddress - is the address of the email recipients it must be of the form "name@place.com" or an error will occur. Use comma or semicolon separator for multiple addresses.
        ccAddress - is the cc address of the email recipients.
        bccAddress - is the bcc address of the email recipients.
        subject - is the subject line of the email message.
        message - is the message to send.
        useHTML - is the flag indicating that the text message is in html format.
        attachments - is a vector of attachments for this email. Each attachment can be a file or a WorkInstruction object.
        Returns:
        A Response object that indicates the status of the message send

      • testEjbMethod

        Response testEjbMethod(int methodDuration,
                       int returnByteSize,
                       boolean throwException)
        Method used for diagnosing problems on the application server. This method will not access the database. It simply will delay for the specified period and return the specified number of bytes. If the method is to throw DatasweepServerException, it will wait for the specified duration before throwing the exception.
        Parameters:
        methodDuration - specifies the amount of time to delay before returning (or throwing the exception) in milliseconds. Specifying a value less than or equal to 0 will return immediately.
        returnByteSize - specifies the number of bytes to return in DBlobData if not throwing the exception. Specifying a value less than 1 will be changed to 1 byte.
        throwException - specifies whether the method should throw DatasweepServerException or not.
        Returns:
        Response. The response will not actually contain the bytes. If an exception was thrown it will be in the response.
